(999, 2, '2011-08-18 15:40:49', '2011-08-18 22:40:49', 'Yes, yes(1) is built-in to Mac and Linux (at least OS X Lion and Ubuntu 11.04). And, as you might guess, it repeatedly prints a string of your choice (''y'' by default) followed by a newline to stdout. Its sole purpose in life is to automate agreeing to prompts. I encountered it recently in a script that was automating RAID array deployment on EC2 ephemeral disks:\r\n<code>\r\n# mdadm doesn''t let you automate by default, so pipe in ''y''!\r\nyes | mdadm ...\r\n</code>', 'yes(1)', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'yes1', '', '', '2011-08-18 15:40:49', '2011-08-18 22:40:49', '', 0, 'http://dan.lecocq.us/wordpress/?p=999', 0, 'post', '', 0),
